# Styling with Tailwind CSS

## Approach
- Use Tailwind utility classes as the primary styling method
- No inline `style={}` props unless absolutely necessary (dynamic values only)
- No new standalone CSS files -- use Tailwind utilities or `@apply` in global CSS
- Use `cn()` (clsx + twMerge) for conditional class merging

## Responsive Design
- Mobile-first: write base styles for mobile, add `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:` for larger screens
- Standard breakpoints: `sm` (640px), `md` (768px), `lg` (1024px), `xl` (1280px)
- Test all pages at 320px, 768px, 1024px, 1440px

## Dark Mode
- Use `dark:` variant for dark mode styles
- Ensure sufficient contrast in both modes (WCAG AA minimum)

## Design Tokens
- Use the custom theme defined in `tailwind.config.js` for colors, spacing, fonts
- Never hard-code color values in className -- use theme tokens

```tsx
// BAD
<div className="bg-[#27374d] text-[#f5f5f5]">

// GOOD
<div className="bg-primary text-primary-foreground">
```

## Component Patterns

```tsx
// Reusable button with variants
interface ButtonProps {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'outline' | 'ghost';
  size?: 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg';
}
```

## Class Ordering
Follow the Tailwind recommended order: layout > sizing > spacing > typography > visual > interactive
- `flex items-center gap-4 w-full p-4 text-sm font-medium bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:bg-gray-50`
